{
  "texts": [
    "Such extreme power density places considerable strain on data center architecture, cooling systems, and power grids.",
    "• Fast and large variability: Across the training, finetuning, and inference phases, AI workloads can be highly variable and bursty [16], with power demand fluctuating sharply over very short timescales and remaining difficult to forecast [17].",
    "For example, large-scale GPU clusters can produce power fluctuations of hundreds of megawatts within only seconds [18], [19], bringing significant challenges for system balancing and reliable grid operation.",
    "• Grid interface via power electronics: AI data centers interface with the power grid primarily through power electronic converters, which exhibit fundamentally different dynamic behaviors from conventional electromechanical loads, such as low inertia, fast response dynamics, and harmonic distortions [20].",
    "At scale, power electronicsbased AI computing loads can pose major threats to grid stability and cause severe power quality issues [21]."
  ]
}